00:28:50.536 --> 00:28:53.376
that there are some types of cancer that can arise more prevalently.

493
00:28:53.896 --> 00:28:54.156
Thank you.

494
00:28:54.716 --> 00:28:55.036
Over here.

495
00:28:56.036 --> 00:28:57.856
It's a great talk. Very inspiring.

496
00:28:58.176 --> 00:29:01.096
I'm just wondering what's the difference between the T cell

497
00:29:01.256 --> 00:29:03.256
co-stimulation, co-inhibition,

498
00:29:04.236 --> 00:29:08.076
interaction versus like the NK cell activation or inhibition?

499
00:29:08.276 --> 00:29:12.006
This is a great question. So T cells get

500
00:29:12.056 --> 00:29:15.866
turned on by seeing their antigen and getting the co-stimulation

501
00:29:15.896 --> 00:29:19.256
versus the co-inhibition. NK cells evolved differently.

502
00:29:19.746 --> 00:29:20.836
They look

503
00:29:22.056 --> 00:29:26.016
for missing self. So NK cells get turned on if they

504
00:29:26.056 --> 00:29:29.696
don't see their self. So they're looking for things, because

505
00:29:29.716 --> 00:29:33.516
viruses and cancer, for instance, turn off MHC, and that's what turns

506
00:29:33.636 --> 00:29:36.856
NK cells off. So NK cells have itchy trigger fingers.

507
00:29:37.276 --> 00:29:40.316
They're ready to kill whenever they see something weird, and they get turned off

508
00:29:40.376 --> 00:29:44.176
all the time. T cells wait, and they get turned on by their

509
00:29:44.256 --> 00:29:44.756
antigen.

510
00:29:46.156 --> 00:29:49.996
Co-inhibition and co-stimulatory molecules are present on NK

511
00:29:50.036 --> 00:29:54.006
cells, but how they interact with the NK cell machinery is still being

512
00:29:54.056 --> 00:29:57.946
heavily looked at. But if, for instance, if you give

513
00:29:57.976 --> 00:30:01.656
an NK cell a CAR, an antigen receptor that's got co-stimulatory

514
00:30:01.716 --> 00:30:03.436
molecules on it, it'll get turned on by that.

515
00:30:04.216 --> 00:30:07.986
But how that matters and what that matters for the fate of

516
00:30:08.056 --> 00:30:11.896
NK cells is still under intense investigation. Great question.

517
00:30:12.176 --> 00:30:12.656
Thank you very much.

518
00:30:13.596 --> 00:30:13.976
Over here.

519
00:30:14.856 --> 00:30:18.596
Thank you for really emphasizing that PD-1 doesn't reverse exhaustion.

520
00:30:18.716 --> 00:30:19.036
Thank you.

521
00:30:19.106 --> 00:30:23.096
My question is, is there anything we can do

522
00:30:23.136 --> 00:30:26.626
with those truly exhausted T cells to reinvigorate the

523
00:30:27.216 --> 00:30:29.146
molecular pathways or other?

524
00:30:29.428 --> 00:30:30.728
Yeah. This is stellar,

525
00:30:32.228 --> 00:30:34.708
right? And this is something that my lab studies quite a bit.

526
00:30:34.988 --> 00:30:37.648
What can we do to get some juice out of these cells?

527
00:30:37.968 --> 00:30:40.628
Because they still do some things. They still make gamma interferon.

528
00:30:40.908 --> 00:30:43.208
They're still full of lytic granules.

529
00:30:43.248 --> 00:30:47.108
They have potential still, but the thing is, their epigenome, they're

530
00:30:47.148 --> 00:30:48.768
just like any other differentiated cell.

531
00:30:48.808 --> 00:30:52.148
It's like asking a skin cell to become a,

532
00:30:53.528 --> 00:30:56.608
I don't know, a liver cell, right? We're talking about differentiation here.

533
00:30:56.648 --> 00:31:00.348
So if we're going to get them to reverse or to

534
00:31:00.368 --> 00:31:04.288
have more potential, we have to be thinking about ways that we can

535
00:31:04.368 --> 00:31:06.088
alter the epigenome or

536
00:31:06.908 --> 00:31:10.618
engineer them in some other way. So cytokines and things like that aren't

537
00:31:10.618 --> 00:31:14.248
necessarily going to do this because most cells can't turn back the

538
00:31:14.288 --> 00:31:17.918
clock. However, there have been lots of individuals thinking about what if we take

539
00:31:17.968 --> 00:31:21.688
out those exhausted T cells and we give them Yamanaka factors

540
00:31:22.008 --> 00:31:23.488
to make them more stem-like. So

541
00:31:24.388 --> 00:31:27.708
can we reverse exhaustion? Maybe, but I think it's going to require something

542
00:31:27.748 --> 00:31:31.668
heroic rather than a simple manipulation.

543
00:31:31.708 --> 00:31:35.698
And so I hope that what we've inspired all of these people to do is

544
00:31:35.708 --> 00:31:37.407
think about that question and hopefully get there.

545
00:31:39.628 --> 00:31:41.598
Oh, we're running... One last question.

546
00:31:43.248 --> 00:31:46.098
Yeah. I just wanted to know what determines

547
00:31:47.228 --> 00:31:51.148
the state of progenitor exhausted T cells versus the

548
00:31:51.208 --> 00:31:52.388
terminal exhausted.

549
00:31:52.948 --> 00:31:56.028
Great. Great question. So a lot of times it's time.

550
00:31:56.448 --> 00:31:59.488
It can also be the degree of stress that the T cell sees.

551
00:31:59.498 --> 00:32:03.318
So when T cells see antigen all the time, it never goes away,

552
00:32:03.348 --> 00:32:07.318
it keeps programming the cell. So the longer it sees antigen, the more

553
00:32:07.348 --> 00:32:10.528
it is going to get driven into that terminally exhausted state.

554
00:32:10.578 --> 00:32:14.518
And so it's a progressive thing. You can actually model this in vitro fairly well,

555
00:32:14.868 --> 00:32:18.398
and the longer you stimulate the T cells, the more terminally differentiated they

556
00:32:18.408 --> 00:32:22.248
become. And so kind of immunology 101, if you open up the book,

557
00:32:23.068 --> 00:32:25.708
Janeway or any other immunobiology, it'll tell you.

558
00:32:25.968 --> 00:32:29.828
If the immune system sees an antigen too much, it's probably self, and so you

559
00:32:29.848 --> 00:32:33.628
should probably not react to it, and so that's just encoded in our immune

560
00:32:33.688 --> 00:32:33.988
system.

561
00:32:35.328 --> 00:32:35.648
Thank you.

562
00:32:36.168 --> 00:32:38.068
All right. Thank you very much for those questions.

563
00:32:44.088 --> 00:32:47.508
Very, very intelligent. I'm really excited about having this conversation.

