00:34:08.649 --> 00:34:12.589
HLA class I, and this peptide is then presented

588
00:34:12.598 --> 00:34:13.828
to the T cell receptor.

589
00:34:14.788 --> 00:34:18.688
These T cells can become activated, produce cytotoxic granules that

590
00:34:19.129 --> 00:34:22.728
then can kill that cancer. But as we've said already,

591
00:34:23.149 --> 00:34:26.208
cancer puts up a good fight and tries to

592
00:34:26.968 --> 00:34:30.948
evade itself so that it can grow and hide from the immune system,

593
00:34:31.169 --> 00:34:33.408
and it does it in a number of ways.

594
00:34:35.248 --> 00:34:39.028
For example, PD-1, PD-L1 interactions, which clinically we are

595
00:34:39.089 --> 00:34:41.408
fighting using checkpoint blockade therapies.

596
00:34:42.688 --> 00:34:46.448
And it's an exciting time in the world of

597
00:34:46.488 --> 00:34:50.408
cancer immunotherapy. Immunotherapies have transformed

598
00:34:50.448 --> 00:34:54.308
the landscape of cancer care, and in fact, most of our

599
00:34:54.589 --> 00:34:58.568
patients are now treated up front with therapies

600
00:34:58.608 --> 00:34:59.168
like this.

601
00:35:00.208 --> 00:35:02.428
Dr. Delgoff has already told you a lot about the

602
00:35:03.268 --> 00:35:06.988
power of checkpoint blockade and how we can use different strategies,

