00:35:26.428 --> 00:35:30.168
There are several forms of adoptive immunotherapy, and I'm going to walk you

609
00:35:30.288 --> 00:35:34.128
through those. After that, I'm going to tell you about our own journey, where

610
00:35:34.188 --> 00:35:37.968
we have found that interestingly, although cytotoxic CD8 T

611
00:35:38.048 --> 00:35:41.838
cells can be leveraged to elicit these potent anti-tumor responses,

612
00:35:41.968 --> 00:35:45.608
especially when they expand them to large numbers, and I'm speaking to the

613
00:35:45.728 --> 00:35:49.697
billions, and then put them back into the patient, that these CD8 T cells

614
00:35:49.728 --> 00:35:53.668
are quite potent. But unfortunately, as you know, some patients

615
00:35:53.688 --> 00:35:55.528
don't respond or relapse after that.

616
00:35:55.988 --> 00:35:59.308
We have found, interestingly, that you can program T cells down

617
00:35:59.348 --> 00:36:02.327
different journeys and elicit the power of this therapy.

618
00:36:02.388 --> 00:36:05.108
So this is really the conversation I want to have with you today.

619
00:36:07.448 --> 00:36:09.208
What is adoptive immunotherapy?

620
00:36:10.508 --> 00:36:14.178
Basic scientists, translational scientists work very closely with

621
00:36:14.178 --> 00:36:17.748
surgeons and medical oncologists to get patient tissue.

622
00:36:17.768 --> 00:36:21.468
For example, this is a patient where we've done surgery, and we can take the

623
00:36:21.508 --> 00:36:22.668
tumor from this patient.

624
00:36:23.968 --> 00:36:27.868
Once we, for example, in our laboratory, get this tumor, we can chop this

625
00:36:27.888 --> 00:36:31.768
tumor up into small pieces and put it into these Petri dishes.

626
00:36:32.288 --> 00:36:36.184
And we give theseInside that tumor lives lots of immune

627
00:36:36.284 --> 00:36:39.844
cells, but they are suppressed by a number of factors.

628
00:36:40.164 --> 00:36:44.084
We can give them the cytokine called IL-2 at high concentrations.

629
00:36:44.144 --> 00:36:45.164
We call them the

630
00:36:46.244 --> 00:36:48.624
T cell food. And these cytokines can

631
00:36:49.444 --> 00:36:53.004
cause a proliferation of these T cells to very large numbers.

632
00:36:53.504 --> 00:36:57.124
In fact, within about three to five weeks, from a small

633
00:36:57.184 --> 00:37:01.084
tissue that's put into a 24-well plate, we can turn

634
00:37:01.144 --> 00:37:05.104
those very few cells into 30 to 50 million

635
00:37:05.164 --> 00:37:08.384
cells. These cells are then obviously cryopreserved.

636
00:37:08.784 --> 00:37:12.744
In situations where patients that are more on PD-1 or

637
00:37:12.804 --> 00:37:14.424
CTLA-4 therapy recur,

638
00:37:15.564 --> 00:37:18.824
we use this type of therapy to treat those patients.

639
00:37:19.284 --> 00:37:22.764
This is called a TIL therapy. These

640
00:37:22.824 --> 00:37:25.064
reactivated T cells are cryopreserved.

641
00:37:25.104 --> 00:37:28.164
We take them out of culture, and we can expand them for another

642
00:37:29.184 --> 00:37:30.284
14

643
00:37:31.124 --> 00:37:34.864
days or sometimes more. And now we're talking

644
00:37:34.904 --> 00:37:37.684
about the billions of cells that are infused into these patients.

645
00:37:38.174 --> 00:37:40.844
And the power of this therapy is undeniable.

646
00:37:40.874 --> 00:37:42.844
And so let me show you what I mean by that.

647
00:37:43.204 --> 00:37:45.984
This is a patient that has triple-negative breast cancer.

648
00:37:46.024 --> 00:37:49.884
And you can see pointed with these yellow arrows, the

649
00:37:49.924 --> 00:37:52.614
tumor burden that this patient is facing.

650
00:37:53.024 --> 00:37:56.904
The patient's head's towards me, the feet are towards you, and this is a CAT scan.

651
00:37:56.944 --> 00:37:58.944
You can really see that there's tumor

652
00:37:59.404 --> 00:38:03.174
in the breast tissue, but this patient's

653
00:38:03.204 --> 00:38:05.344
tumor is also metastasized to the liver.

654
00:38:05.444 --> 00:38:07.774
You can see very large tumor masses.

655
00:38:09.744 --> 00:38:13.504
When this cell therapy is infused into these patients, you can see

656
00:38:13.564 --> 00:38:16.544
this particular patient experienced a phenomenal result.

657
00:38:16.884 --> 00:38:20.634
You can see within 22 months later, this patient has actually had

658
00:38:20.684 --> 00:38:23.194
a curative response, which is quite rare.

659
00:38:24.544 --> 00:38:26.784
And I was very fortunate to actually meet this patient.

660
00:38:26.814 --> 00:38:30.424
I trained at the National Institutes of Health a long time ago, and

661
00:38:31.304 --> 00:38:33.684
Steven Rosenberg has developed this work.

662
00:38:33.744 --> 00:38:37.644
He started this work in 1986. And then two years

663
00:38:37.684 --> 00:38:40.464
ago, this therapy has now become FDA approved.

664
00:38:41.604 --> 00:38:45.344
And why did that happen? This is a landmark paper from the "New

665
00:38:45.404 --> 00:38:48.954
England Journal of Medicine" showing the power of adoptive

666
00:38:48.964 --> 00:38:52.334
immunotherapy when compared to checkpoint blockade therapy.

667
00:38:53.044 --> 00:38:56.404
And in this clinical trial, 84 patients per arm

668
00:38:56.484 --> 00:38:57.604
were treated,

669
00:38:58.424 --> 00:39:01.524
and these patients had relapsed from checkpoint blockade therapy.

670
00:39:02.884 --> 00:39:06.584
The patients were either given ipilimumab, which is a CTLA-4 blocking

