00:40:19.444 --> 00:40:22.644
using PowerPoint. I've already told you about the first one, right?

692
00:40:22.904 --> 00:40:26.484
In yellow, where we can take the tissue, the

693
00:40:26.544 --> 00:40:29.894
tumor, use cytokines to expand these cells to large number.

694
00:40:30.024 --> 00:40:32.004
This is TIL therapy.

695
00:40:32.894 --> 00:40:36.514
Motivated by this work, it had been appreciated that some patients,

696
00:40:38.744 --> 00:40:42.184
we simply can't generate a TIL product, or in

697
00:40:42.224 --> 00:40:45.524
certain patients, this TIL product is not quite therapeutic.

698
00:40:46.154 --> 00:40:49.184
What do we do next? We can sequence these tumors,

699
00:40:49.904 --> 00:40:52.884
understand the tumor antigens and the mutations that Dr.

700
00:40:53.023 --> 00:40:56.764
Delgoff talked about, and then identify T cell

701
00:40:56.804 --> 00:41:00.344
receptors that recognize those specific mutations and

702
00:41:00.364 --> 00:41:04.184
deliberately genetically engineer a human T cell with a TCR

703
00:41:04.444 --> 00:41:06.964
instead of this bulk TIL product where we have

704
00:41:09.264 --> 00:41:13.084
probably several different types of T cell responses happening because

705
00:41:13.124 --> 00:41:15.264
there's polyclonal TIL products.

706
00:41:16.584 --> 00:41:19.484
And this was first done at the NIH by Laura Johnson.

707
00:41:20.024 --> 00:41:23.154
And what she did is take the peripheral blood of these patients,

708
00:41:23.584 --> 00:41:27.064
genetically engineer the T cell receptor with a mutated

