nucleotide variations, but they could be structural variations as well.

1204
01:10:03.868 --> 01:10:07.088
Cancer cells may also have changes in their epigenetic states.

1205
01:10:07.428 --> 01:10:11.008
And combined, this may lead to signaling and

1206
01:10:11.068 --> 01:10:14.168
transcriptional programs that may stimulate or

1207
01:10:14.368 --> 01:10:18.248
inhibit the immune response. So on the level of a cancer

1208
01:10:18.328 --> 01:10:21.708
cell, this may mean that the cancer cell either upregulates

1209
01:10:22.088 --> 01:10:25.908
specific antigens, including MHC molecules, but they may also suppress

1210
01:10:26.048 --> 01:10:29.998
expression of the MHCs. Cancer cells may produce certain types of

1211
01:10:30.028 --> 01:10:33.568
cytokines and chemokines that may help to recruit

1212
01:10:34.008 --> 01:10:36.048
other cells to the tumor microenvironment.

1213
01:10:36.508 --> 01:10:40.468
And these cells may be both immunostimulatory and inhibitory.

1214
01:10:40.978 --> 01:10:44.748
The process becomes complicated by these cells interacting

1215
01:10:44.868 --> 01:10:48.108
back with the cancer cells and inducing additional programs.

1216
01:10:48.628 --> 01:10:52.248
And then the context matters as well, because these cancers may be present in

1217
01:10:52.288 --> 01:10:56.258
different organs, either in the organs that they arise, but also in

1218
01:10:56.288 --> 01:10:58.088
the organs that they metastasize to.

1219
01:10:58.167 --> 01:11:01.708
So the local tissue environment where these cancers are present can

1220
01:11:01.808 --> 01:11:04.788
further promote or inhibit the immune response.

1221
01:11:04.828 --> 01:11:08.138
And we know from emerging data that, for example, cancers that

1222
01:11:08.168 --> 01:11:12.048
metastasize to the liver tend to be more immunosuppressive, not

1223
01:11:12.128 --> 01:11:15.448
just locally, but even systemically as well.

1224
01:11:16.088 --> 01:11:19.568
And then even if we look within the context of a specific tumor,

1225
01:11:19.948 --> 01:11:23.868
these cancer cells further divide into individual clones.

1226
01:11:23.948 --> 01:11:27.418
Again, these could be mutational clones, but also epigenetically driven,

1227
01:11:28.048 --> 01:11:32.008
that further contribute to this kind of a heterogeneity where you can have even

1228
01:11:32.048 --> 01:11:35.748
within one tumor or multiple tumors, essentially these

1229
01:11:35.808 --> 01:11:39.388
populations that have distinct tumor microenvironment states.

1230
01:11:39.788 --> 01:11:43.048
They may have distinct T cell receptor repertoires and distinct

1231
01:11:43.288 --> 01:11:46.908
activities or activation states of these T cells.

1232
01:11:47.828 --> 01:11:51.708
How does that look in clinic? Or if we see, let's say, a patient's tumor

1233
01:11:51.768 --> 01:11:52.508
on a slide,

1234
01:11:53.328 --> 01:11:54.328
what does that mean? So

1235
01:11:55.968 --> 01:11:59.908
as we try to develop biomarkers to predict who are the patients

1236
01:11:59.948 --> 01:12:03.508
that will respond to therapy, we have learned over a number of years

1237
01:12:04.228 --> 01:12:08.108
to classify them into tumors which we think are going to respond, and the

1238
01:12:08.148 --> 01:12:10.948
tumors that we think will not are going to respond.

1239
01:12:12.108 --> 01:12:15.868
And as Dr. Delgoff has mentioned, this

1240
01:12:15.948 --> 01:12:19.628
is usually based on the basis of whether these

1241
01:12:19.688 --> 01:12:23.508
tumors have T cells in them or not. So on the one end of the

1242
01:12:23.608 --> 01:12:27.208
spectrum, we have these tumors that we call cold, and the whole

1243
01:12:27.388 --> 01:12:30.808
concept of cold versus hot tumors is really just

1244
01:12:30.848 --> 01:12:34.508
defined by the presence or absence of tumor-infiltrating

1245
01:12:34.588 --> 01:12:38.408
lymphocytes. So the cold tumors tend not to have any T

1246
01:12:38.468 --> 01:12:41.508
cells, neither in the tumor core or in the

1247
01:12:41.548 --> 01:12:45.108
stroma.There are multiple potential mechanisms that may lead

1248
01:12:45.168 --> 01:12:48.688
to the cold tumors. But in the context of what we call primary

1249
01:12:48.748 --> 01:12:52.428
resistance, we often think that these are the tumors that maybe never were

1250
01:12:52.438 --> 01:12:55.248
recognized by the immune system in the first place.

1251
01:12:55.328 --> 01:12:58.948
Maybe they didn't have the antigens that were strong enough to

1252
01:12:59.028 --> 01:13:02.528
stimulate the tumor-specific immune response, or maybe they had the

1253
01:13:02.608 --> 01:13:05.628
antigens, but through certain inhibitory mechanisms,

1254
01:13:06.528 --> 01:13:10.448
these antigens were not presented, hence the T cell priming never happened,

1255
01:13:10.468 --> 01:13:14.198
and these tumors are just living there by themselves without the T cells.

1256
01:13:14.968 --> 01:13:17.988
Next, we have what we call excluded tumors.

1257
01:13:18.068 --> 01:13:21.988
So these tumors may have T cells in the stroma, but not directly in

1258
01:13:22.028 --> 01:13:25.808
the tumor core. So these cancers may actually

1259
01:13:25.848 --> 01:13:29.768
have evidence of the initial T cell priming, but these T cells are

1260
01:13:29.808 --> 01:13:33.688
not able to make it into the tumor, and this could be driven by

1261
01:13:33.748 --> 01:13:37.168
multiple mechanisms. Some of these are purely

1262
01:13:37.208 --> 01:13:38.128
mechanical. There's

1263
01:13:38.988 --> 01:13:42.668
lack of permeability of your cancers to these T cells.

1264
01:13:43.068 --> 01:13:47.028
These could be vascular and stromal factors or presence of a very suppressive

1265
01:13:47.048 --> 01:13:49.608
tumor microenvironment that keeps these cells out.

1266
01:13:49.868 --> 01:13:53.608
So obviously, these T cells cannot mediate the tumor killing.

1267
01:13:54.468 --> 01:13:57.968
Next, we have the hot tumors. These are the tumors we like to have.

1268
01:13:58.208 --> 01:14:01.508
These tumors have T cells in the tumor. They have them in the stroma.

1269
01:14:02.128 --> 01:14:05.508
These T cells exhibit markers of T cell

1270
01:14:05.668 --> 01:14:09.458
activation, and often they exhibit markers of T cell exhaustion.

1271
01:14:09.928 --> 01:14:13.768
We actually like to see T cell exhaustion in the tumors, not because we

1272
01:14:13.808 --> 01:14:17.708
can reverse that exhaustion, but because exhaustion serves as a marker that

1273
01:14:17.728 --> 01:14:21.428
the T cells have made it to the tumor, they have interacted with these cancer

1274
01:14:21.528 --> 01:14:24.748
cells, and were able to upregulate these T cell exhaustion

1275
01:14:25.248 --> 01:14:25.808
machinery.

1276
01:14:27.368 --> 01:14:30.488
This is what we call an adaptive immune resistance.

1277
01:14:30.548 --> 01:14:34.248
It's essentially, again, the cancer was recognized by the immune

1278
01:14:34.328 --> 01:14:38.068
cells, and it adapted itself to resist

1279
01:14:38.348 --> 01:14:42.148
the immune response. And then finally, we get to the state that we

1280
01:14:42.188 --> 01:14:45.928
call edited. So in the context of this chronic

1281
01:14:46.008 --> 01:14:49.508
interaction with the immune cells, the cancer cells

1282
01:14:49.828 --> 01:14:53.388
develop further mechanisms that help them to

1283
01:14:53.448 --> 01:14:57.348
avoid the immune response. And these edited

1284
01:14:57.468 --> 01:15:01.068
tumors, they can be cold, they can be excluded, or they could be hot.

1285
01:15:01.288 --> 01:15:05.108
And it all depends where you catch that tumor, which state you catch the

1286
01:15:05.148 --> 01:15:09.108
tumor in when you are performing that tumor biopsy or the

1287
01:15:09.148 --> 01:15:10.008
tumor resection.

1288
01:15:10.888 --> 01:15:14.658
And the editing may happen if you lose the specific antigens that the immune

1289
01:15:14.728 --> 01:15:15.728
system recognizes.

1290
01:15:16.548 --> 01:15:20.088
You may lose the antigen presentation machinery or MHC

1291
01:15:20.128 --> 01:15:24.028
molecules, and then there are certain signaling pathways that may be downregulated

1292
01:15:24.068 --> 01:15:26.808
within these cancer cells, such as interferon gamma signaling.

1293
01:15:27.088 --> 01:15:31.048
But in the end, eventually you can get to the state of a cold tumors again,

1294
01:15:31.108 --> 01:15:34.868
where these are, even though the tumors originally had the

1295
01:15:34.888 --> 01:15:38.628
ability to be recognized by the immune system, they are no longer able

1296
01:15:38.668 --> 01:15:38.908
to.

1297
01:15:40.448 --> 01:15:44.408
So with this in mind, what are the potential biomarkers we

1298
01:15:44.448 --> 01:15:48.268
can use to predict who are the patients that will respond to these therapies?

1299
01:15:48.388 --> 01:15:52.188
And I'm mainly talking about immune checkpoint inhibitors, but this will probably

1300
01:15:52.208 --> 01:15:54.308
span to the other types of immunotherapies

1301
01:15:55.188 --> 01:15:59.068
as well. So when we talk about the determinants of immune

1302
01:15:59.128 --> 01:16:02.948
recognition across cancers, we broadly like to divide them

1303
01:16:03.008 --> 01:16:06.648
into the genetic determinants as well as an immune or the tumor

1304
01:16:06.708 --> 01:16:08.288
microenvironment determinants.

1305
01:16:08.548 --> 01:16:12.038
There are other extra determinants that may happen in our

1306
01:16:12.048 --> 01:16:15.948
environment as well. For example, sometimes we look at the

1307
01:16:16.188 --> 01:16:19.648
gut microbiome that may contribute, but ultimately all of

1308
01:16:19.688 --> 01:16:22.488
these impact of what is happening in the tumor.

1309
01:16:23.228 --> 01:16:27.208
So by genetic determinants, I may refer to the actual

1310
01:16:27.248 --> 01:16:31.058
germline determinants, but also, more commonly, we talk about what are

1311
01:16:31.088 --> 01:16:33.448
the mutations that are happening in the tumor.

1312
01:16:33.548 --> 01:16:37.148
So we'll look at the specific mutations that may

1313
01:16:37.188 --> 01:16:40.908
lead to generation of these new antigens or neoepitopes,

1314
01:16:41.368 --> 01:16:44.648
or potential mutations that may suppress the immune response.

1315
01:16:45.168 --> 01:16:48.968
Ultimately, these mutations is what leads to the tumor

1316
01:16:49.008 --> 01:16:49.798
immunogenicity.

1317
01:16:50.668 --> 01:16:54.348
Of course, the mutations by themselves, even if they produce these immunogenic

1318
01:16:54.428 --> 01:16:58.208
novel proteins, are not sufficient, so we'll have to look at the actual

1319
01:16:58.328 --> 01:17:00.428
MHC subtype of the patient as well.

1320
01:17:00.848 --> 01:17:03.528
And there have been a number of studies that have demonstrated that you have a

1321
01:17:03.588 --> 01:17:07.488
broad diversity of your MHC repertoire, you will have

1322
01:17:07.548 --> 01:17:11.488
a higher likelihood of presenting that antigen to the immune system.

1323
01:17:12.068 --> 01:17:15.948
And then on the other end of the MHC, we also have a T cell receptor,

1324
01:17:16.688 --> 01:17:20.248
which is what's ultimately going to recognize these antigens.

1325
01:17:20.328 --> 01:17:24.008
And a number of studies have also demonstrated that if you have a broad

1326
01:17:24.018 --> 01:17:27.548
diversity of your T cell receptor repertoire, there's a higher

1327
01:17:27.668 --> 01:17:31.358
likelihood that you may have a precursor T cell that would be specific

1328
01:17:31.768 --> 01:17:35.708
for that antigen. On the level of the tumor microenvironment, we can look

1329
01:17:36.428 --> 01:17:39.408
at the number of the specific immune cells

1330
01:17:40.308 --> 01:17:43.588
that you have in the tumor, their phenotypic states,

1331
01:17:44.328 --> 01:17:47.888
maybe some interactions of the cells with each other, and presence of certain

1332
01:17:47.988 --> 01:17:50.868
ligands that we could potentially target.

1333
01:17:51.048 --> 01:17:54.988
So I'm going to start with the tumor mutational burden as a biomarker because this

1334
01:17:55.048 --> 01:17:58.708
is one of the earliest approved biomarkers that we have had for immune

1335
01:17:58.748 --> 01:18:02.608
checkpoint blockade. Tumor mutational burden, as the name implies,

1336
01:18:02.928 --> 01:18:06.688
just measures the number of mutations that we have when we

1337
01:18:06.728 --> 01:18:09.168
perform certain types of sequencing.

1338
01:18:09.268 --> 01:18:13.128
So as you can imagine, the higher the number of mutations, the

1339
01:18:13.188 --> 01:18:16.008
higher is the likelihood that that tumor will produce

1340
01:18:18.368 --> 01:18:21.698
what we call neoepitopes or immunogenic peptides that would be then

1341
01:18:21.698 --> 01:18:23.968
presented through the proteasome and

1342
01:18:25.548 --> 01:18:29.258
processed to be presented on MHC class 1, and

1343
01:18:29.288 --> 01:18:32.138
sometimes MHC class 2 on the surface of cancer cells.

1344
01:18:32.898 --> 01:18:36.808
And there are certain cancers that have higher mutational

1345
01:18:36.828 --> 01:18:40.478
burden. The best example are cancers that are driven by

1346
01:18:40.588 --> 01:18:42.732
mismatch repair deficiency, such as...

1347
01:18:42.742 --> 01:18:45.412
such as certain types of colorectal and endometrial cancer.

1348
01:18:46.152 --> 01:18:49.492
These are the cancers that have the highest response to immune checkpoint

1349
01:18:49.552 --> 01:18:53.212
inhibitors. In addition to these genetic drivers,

1350
01:18:53.472 --> 01:18:57.312
you may also have cancers that are resulting as

1351
01:18:57.412 --> 01:19:01.212
a response to certain carcinogens, such as UV light in the

1352
01:19:01.252 --> 01:19:04.892
setting of melanoma and tobacco smoking in the setting of lung

1353
01:19:04.992 --> 01:19:08.732
cancer. And again, high mutational burden in these cancers has been

1354
01:19:08.792 --> 01:19:11.712
shown to be associated with better response.

1355
01:19:12.292 --> 01:19:15.542
And again, this is probably best exemplified by studies like this.

1356
01:19:15.892 --> 01:19:19.812
These are two randomized clinical trials of chemotherapy with

1357
01:19:20.132 --> 01:19:23.432
or without PD-1 inhibitors in patients with endometrial cancer.

1358
01:19:23.852 --> 01:19:27.812
I'm biased because I treat endometrial cancer, but this is still a good

1359
01:19:27.852 --> 01:19:31.752
example. At the top, you have patients with MSI high cancers.

1360
01:19:31.812 --> 01:19:35.772
At the bottom, you have patients that just have microsatellite stable or

1361
01:19:35.812 --> 01:19:39.692
low mutational burden cancers. And you can see that in these types

1362
01:19:39.752 --> 01:19:43.132
of cancers, this mismatch repair deficiency or high

1363
01:19:43.192 --> 01:19:46.992
mutational burden are strongly associated with benefit

1364
01:19:47.052 --> 01:19:50.612
from addition of immunotherapy, in this case, dostarlimab

1365
01:19:50.952 --> 01:19:54.832
or pembrolizumab. I should also point to

1366
01:19:54.872 --> 01:19:58.652
the fact that even though you do have a high mutational

1367
01:19:58.712 --> 01:20:01.612
burden, it's not predictive in 100% of cases.

1368
01:20:01.652 --> 01:20:04.832
And in both cases, there's still about 30% of the patients that do not

1369
01:20:04.912 --> 01:20:08.831
respond to these therapies. But this is certainly a good

1370
01:20:09.412 --> 01:20:12.992
start. So if we cannot predict this on the basis of

1371
01:20:13.012 --> 01:20:16.772
genetics alone, again, we'll like to look at the tumor microenvironment,

1372
01:20:17.852 --> 01:20:21.672
because this is essentially where the immune response is

1373
01:20:21.712 --> 01:20:25.672
happening. When we look at the tumor microenvironment, we can of course

1374
01:20:25.752 --> 01:20:28.492
look at the T cell numbers and their location.

1375
01:20:28.552 --> 01:20:30.952
Are they in the tumors or are they extracellular?

1376
01:20:31.032 --> 01:20:34.692
Again, as what I have called before, hot tumors versus cold

1377
01:20:34.732 --> 01:20:37.992
tumors. But this is a very non-specific measure,

1378
01:20:38.672 --> 01:20:42.572
just because many of these T cells were actually found not to be tumor specific.

1379
01:20:42.712 --> 01:20:46.292
Just because you have a T cell in the tumor doesn't mean it's recognizing your

1380
01:20:46.332 --> 01:20:50.292
tumor. And in fact, many viral specific T cells, such as the ones

1381
01:20:50.332 --> 01:20:53.792
that are maybe recognizing Epstein-Barr virus or

1382
01:20:53.852 --> 01:20:57.042
CMV or influenza, can be found in the tumors.

1383
01:20:57.712 --> 01:21:01.512
What we'd like to look at is actual T cell phenotypes, because certain

1384
01:21:01.532 --> 01:21:05.232
phenotypes like activated T cells or dysfunctional T cells

1385
01:21:06.052 --> 01:21:09.962
are an actual evidence that these T cells have encountered an antigen in the

1386
01:21:09.992 --> 01:21:12.712
tumor and have upregulated these programs.

1387
01:21:13.352 --> 01:21:16.772
We can also look at the tumor microenvironment phenotypes such as expression of

1388
01:21:16.792 --> 01:21:18.752
certain ligands like PD-L1.

1389
01:21:19.792 --> 01:21:23.712
And increasingly, we're not just looking at these markers in

1390
01:21:23.772 --> 01:21:27.232
isolation. What we'd like to look at is at the interaction between these different

1391
01:21:27.272 --> 01:21:29.792
cells in the tumor microenvironment.

1392
01:21:30.372 --> 01:21:34.052
So PD-L1 expression is probably one of the most commonly

1393
01:21:34.112 --> 01:21:37.812
used biomarkers because it is an approved biomarker in clinic for

1394
01:21:37.852 --> 01:21:41.752
certain cancer types. This is an example of a study in lung

1395
01:21:41.872 --> 01:21:45.272
cancer demonstrating how selection of patients by

1396
01:21:45.292 --> 01:21:49.172
PD-L1 expression can help to identify the patients that are

1397
01:21:49.232 --> 01:21:50.452
more likely to benefit

1398
01:21:51.312 --> 01:21:54.852
from drugs like pembrolizumab, which is a PD-1 inhibitor.

1399
01:21:55.312 --> 01:21:56.612
And in this case, using the

1400
01:21:58.352 --> 01:22:01.772
PD-L1 expression score of 50% or

1401
01:22:01.952 --> 01:22:05.621
above, we can readily identify the patients who may benefit from

1402
01:22:06.172 --> 01:22:09.952
this therapy, and in fact, FDA used this biomarker as an

1403
01:22:09.992 --> 01:22:13.912
approval. But this is probably one of the best examples where this biomarker

1404
01:22:13.932 --> 01:22:17.152
works. I can honestly tell you that in the majority of the

1405
01:22:17.212 --> 01:22:21.082
cancers, PD-L1 actually either doesn't work or

1406
01:22:21.152 --> 01:22:24.772
it doesn't result in such a broad differential.

1407
01:22:24.872 --> 01:22:28.332
So what else can we look at? So we have to look

1408
01:22:28.372 --> 01:22:31.832
beyond PD-L1. And again, this is an example where

1409
01:22:32.272 --> 01:22:35.432
we're looking at the other cells in the microenvironment and their interactions

1410
01:22:35.452 --> 01:22:37.032
with other cells can be useful.

1411
01:22:37.832 --> 01:22:41.822
So again, as Dr. Delgoff has mentioned, we can look at the

1412
01:22:41.892 --> 01:22:45.512
presence of dysfunctional T cells or early dysfunctional T

1413
01:22:45.572 --> 01:22:46.572
cells in the tumor

1414
01:22:47.612 --> 01:22:51.252
microenvironment, and we can define them by presence of certain markers

1415
01:22:51.852 --> 01:22:54.112
that are expressed on the surface.

1416
01:22:54.652 --> 01:22:57.432
Again, these cells don't exist in isolation.

1417
01:22:57.732 --> 01:23:01.512
We can look at potentially in proximity of whether these cells

1418
01:23:01.591 --> 01:23:02.072
exist

1419
01:23:03.432 --> 01:23:07.172
close to other cancer cells or immune cells in the

1420
01:23:07.412 --> 01:23:11.312
microenvironment that are expressing PD-L1. Why is that important?

1421
01:23:11.472 --> 01:23:13.262
Well, as Dr. Delgoff has mentioned,

1422
01:23:14.092 --> 01:23:17.762
normally if you have the T cells that are recognizing tumor antigens, they will

1423
01:23:17.792 --> 01:23:21.652
produce interferon gamma. This interferon gamma will bind to interferon

1424
01:23:21.752 --> 01:23:25.032
gamma receptor on cancer cells or immune cells, and that's what leads to

1425
01:23:25.092 --> 01:23:28.832
PD-L1 upregulation. So we know that the distance of interferon

1426
01:23:28.892 --> 01:23:31.752
gamma action is approximately 30 to 50 microns.

1427
01:23:32.202 --> 01:23:35.922
So if we look even in a static tumor and

1428
01:23:37.712 --> 01:23:41.172
measure the interaction between the T cells and these

1429
01:23:41.212 --> 01:23:44.452
PD-L1 positive cancer cells on immune cells, this can

1430
01:23:46.712 --> 01:23:50.592
be used as a surrogate marker that this T cell is active or

1431
01:23:50.692 --> 01:23:54.672
it has been active in the past. And we

1432
01:23:54.712 --> 01:23:58.692
can use these kinds of measurements to actually predict, again, whether the patient

1433
01:23:58.752 --> 01:24:02.672
is more or less likely to benefit from the immunotherapy just on the basis of

1434
01:24:02.682 --> 01:24:05.682
presence of these cells and their interaction with

1435
01:24:06.992 --> 01:24:08.432
the other cells in the microenvironment.

1436
01:24:08.452 --> 01:24:11.962
And again, this is an example of a study that we did demonstrating that just

1437
01:24:12.032 --> 01:24:15.292
presence of these PD-1 positive cells in a tumor microenvironment,

1438
01:24:15.912 --> 01:24:19.292
but more importantly, their proximity with other

1439
01:24:19.312 --> 01:24:23.272
