1441
01:24:26.072 --> 01:24:29.952
But there are other kinds of interactions we can measure

1442
01:24:29.992 --> 01:24:33.392
as well. And again, the more we learn about the biology

1443
01:24:34.132 --> 01:24:37.702
of our tumors, the more things we can look at. Again, Dr.

1444
01:24:37.952 --> 01:24:41.452
Paulus has highlighted the importance of CD4

1445
01:24:41.472 --> 01:24:44.320
cells, which mayHave been underappreciated before.

1446
01:24:44.400 --> 01:24:46.760
Well, there are a couple of very nice studies.

1447
01:24:46.860 --> 01:24:49.500
One is from Andrea Schietinger's group,

1448
01:24:50.120 --> 01:24:53.940
and this one is from Miriam Merad's group, demonstrating that a

1449
01:24:54.100 --> 01:24:57.300
presence of interactions with other cells in the tumor

1450
01:24:57.340 --> 01:25:01.200
microenvironment, in this case, the triads between dendritic cells,

1451
01:25:01.400 --> 01:25:05.020
CD4 T cells, and CD8 T cells,

1452
01:25:05.520 --> 01:25:09.380
is what's probably most predictive of responses to immunotherapy, in

1453
01:25:09.420 --> 01:25:12.720
this case, in the hepatocellular carcinoma, and on the bottom to

1454
01:25:14.140 --> 01:25:15.520
malignant mesothelioma,

1455
01:25:16.600 --> 01:25:19.200
or in the context of adaptive cell therapies.

1456
01:25:19.600 --> 01:25:23.200
And there's beautiful biology that goes into this to demonstrate how the CD4 T

1457
01:25:23.260 --> 01:25:27.220
cells provide the help to the CD8 T cells to license them and

1458
01:25:27.240 --> 01:25:30.140
reprogram them to become functional.

1459
01:25:30.720 --> 01:25:34.710
So again, the more we'll learn about the biology, the more markers we could

1460
01:25:34.740 --> 01:25:36.070
potentially use. But

1461
01:25:36.980 --> 01:25:40.520
what I want to highlight is that if we want to translate these kinds of markers to

1462
01:25:40.540 --> 01:25:43.300
patients, it's not necessarily that difficult.

1463
01:25:43.440 --> 01:25:47.419
When we do these kinds of analysis, we start very broad, but we can usually narrow

1464
01:25:47.460 --> 01:25:51.120
them down to two or three markers that can be implemented in a

1465
01:25:51.500 --> 01:25:54.780
routine clinical IHC-based types of assays.

1466
01:25:55.500 --> 01:25:59.190
Lastly, we can also look at the T cell receptor repertoires

1467
01:25:59.880 --> 01:26:03.800
from these patients, as they can also offer clues into the specificity of

1468
01:26:03.840 --> 01:26:05.300
the immune response. If you just

1469
01:26:06.600 --> 01:26:10.560
sequence your T cell receptor repertoires, you usually don't know what those T

1470
01:26:10.640 --> 01:26:13.260
cells may be recognizing. But emergently,

1471
01:26:14.160 --> 01:26:18.080
we can look at patterns of these T cell receptors based on

1472
01:26:18.100 --> 01:26:21.990
the sequence, but also on their sharing between the different tumor sites or

1473
01:26:22.260 --> 01:26:25.400
on their sharing between the blood and the tumor.

1474
01:26:25.820 --> 01:26:29.800
And if we see, for example, if we have tumor-infiltrating T cells

1475
01:26:29.840 --> 01:26:33.820
that are expanding in peripheral blood in response to therapy, sometimes we

1476
01:26:33.860 --> 01:26:37.520
can use this as a surrogate marker of systemic anti-tumor immune

1477
01:26:37.580 --> 01:26:40.220
response. And here is an example of such a study.

1478
01:26:40.280 --> 01:26:43.800
This was published by Dr. Kai Wucherpfennig's group a few years ago.

1479
01:26:44.340 --> 01:26:48.180
This was in the setting of a clinical trial of patients with head and neck

1480
01:26:48.220 --> 01:26:52.100
