1489
01:27:21.720 --> 01:27:25.700
anti-tumor activity. I have three minutes left, so I'm going to use

1490
01:27:25.760 --> 01:27:27.920
that to cover the immunotherapy toxicities.

1491
01:27:28.920 --> 01:27:32.680
So nothing is free. So many of the therapies that we use

1492
01:27:33.280 --> 01:27:36.880
come with certain risks. So starting with immune checkpoint

1493
01:27:36.920 --> 01:27:40.820
inhibitors, we do get these, what we call

1494
01:27:40.900 --> 01:27:43.600
immune-related adverse events or IRAEs.

1495
01:27:44.500 --> 01:27:47.920
And this is because activation of immune system is not perfect.

1496
01:27:48.180 --> 01:27:51.760
And then so these immune-related adverse events result from inappropriate

1497
01:27:51.840 --> 01:27:55.449
recognition of normal tissues by T cells, and this can lead to these

1498
01:27:55.520 --> 01:27:57.660
autoimmune-like tissue destruction.

1499
01:27:58.240 --> 01:28:02.160
In most of the cases, it is very mild, but in some cases it's not.

1500
01:28:02.300 --> 01:28:04.940
So early recognition of this is

1501
01:28:05.800 --> 01:28:09.620
essential. These T cells may affect essentially any

1502
01:28:09.700 --> 01:28:13.060
organ in the body, but we know that there are certain organs that are more affected

1503
01:28:13.080 --> 01:28:13.640
than others.

1504
01:28:14.520 --> 01:28:17.460
Different classes of checkpoint inhibitors are associated with different

1505
01:28:17.500 --> 01:28:21.380
toxicities, but any immune-related adverse event can occur

1506
01:28:21.420 --> 01:28:25.200
with any agent. And it's very important to distinguish them from

1507
01:28:25.240 --> 01:28:28.500
other causes, especially infectious causes or underlying disease.

1508
01:28:28.880 --> 01:28:32.500
Again, as I mentioned, most of these toxicities are very manageable,

1509
01:28:33.040 --> 01:28:36.850
but some are associated with significant morbidity

1510
01:28:37.360 --> 01:28:41.220
and even mortality. So, for example, if you look at the

1511
01:28:41.280 --> 01:28:44.560
study that was published now seven years ago or eight years ago,

1512
01:28:45.180 --> 01:28:49.160
just looking at the number of cases and fatality rates that you get from certain

1513
01:28:49.340 --> 01:28:52.000
immune checkpoint inhibitors, you can see that certain

1514
01:28:53.360 --> 01:28:56.420
toxicities, such as myocarditis, can be quite

1515
01:28:56.700 --> 01:29:00.250
substantial and even lethal. Close to 40% of the patients that

1516
01:29:00.280 --> 01:29:04.240
develop myocarditis, which is inflammation in the heart, can die from

1517
01:29:04.980 --> 01:29:08.660
this therapy. How do we usually treat immune-related adverse

1518
01:29:08.720 --> 01:29:10.700
events? It all depends on the severity.

1519
01:29:11.020 --> 01:29:14.660
Mild cases can just be followed. The patients with moderate

1520
01:29:14.720 --> 01:29:16.820
symptoms usually require some steroids.

1521
01:29:17.380 --> 01:29:20.800
But then patients with more severe symptoms typically need to

1522
01:29:21.680 --> 01:29:25.210
be admitted to the hospital, get systemic intravenous steroids, and

1523
01:29:25.220 --> 01:29:29.010
potentially other immunomodulatory antibodies as well.

1524
01:29:29.080 --> 01:29:32.660
Adaptive cell therapies are associated with their own set of immune

1525
01:29:32.700 --> 01:29:36.440
toxicities. One of the types of toxicities we can look at is the

1526
01:29:36.480 --> 01:29:40.060
tissue damage that can result from on-target, off-tumor

1527
01:29:40.160 --> 01:29:43.740
effect, basically recognition of shared antigens on normal

1528
01:29:43.840 --> 01:29:47.500
tissues. Dr. Paules did mention that some of these adaptive cell

1529
01:29:47.540 --> 01:29:51.140
therapies, such as targeting B cell malignancies, will effectively

1530
01:29:51.180 --> 01:29:53.440
eliminate your normal B cells as well.

1531
01:29:54.560 --> 01:29:58.320
So that's an example. The more common things that we observe are what we call

1532
01:29:58.360 --> 01:30:02.140
cytokine release syndrome. This is a systemic inflammatory reaction that can be

1533
01:30:02.240 --> 01:30:05.520
caused by inflammatory factors that are released by these activated

1534
01:30:06.580 --> 01:30:08.760
immune cells. This is a systemic response.

1535
01:30:09.160 --> 01:30:10.600
You can also have a response,

1536
01:30:11.460 --> 01:30:15.380
which is neurologic. It's called ICANS or immune effector cell-associated

1537
01:30:15.580 --> 01:30:19.480
neurotoxicity syndrome. It is mediated by a different mechanism.

1538
01:30:19.760 --> 01:30:23.220
It's not exactly clear of how it happens, but it has been suggested to

1539
01:30:23.300 --> 01:30:27.160
